<section xml:id="section-systems-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl>

	<li>
		<title>linear equation</title>
		<idx><h>linear</h><h>equation</h></idx>
		<idx><h>equation(s)</h><h>linear</h></idx>
		<p>an equation of the form <me>\text{number times variable plus number times variable plus }\dots \text{ equals number}</me></p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>system of linear equations</title>
		<idx><h>system</h><h>of linear equations</h></idx>
		<idx><h>equation(s)</h><h>system of</h></idx>
		<p>a (finite) collection of linear equations</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<note><p>
We will often just say <term>system of equations</term> to mean a system of linear equations.
</p></note>

<p><dl>

	<li>
		<title>solution</title>
		<idx><h>solution</h><h>to a system of linear equations</h></idx>
		<idx><h>system</h><h>solution</h></idx>
		<p>a set of values that, when substituted in for the variables of a system of equations, satisfy all of the equations in the system simultaneously</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>solution set</title>
		<idx><h>solution</h><h>set</h></idx>
		<p>the collection of all possible solutions to a system of equations</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>consistent system</title>
		<idx><h>consistent system</h></idx>
		<idx><h>system</h><h>consistent</h></idx>
		<p>a system of equations with at least one solution</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>inconsistent system</title>
		<idx><h>inconsistent system</h></idx>
		<idx><h>system</h><h>inconsistent</h></idx>
		<p>a system of equations with no solution</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>parametric equations</title>
		<idx><h>parametric equations</h></idx>
		<idx><h>equation(s)</h><h>parametric</h></idx>
		<p>a collection of formulas, based on one or more parameters, for the variables in a linear system that represent all possible solutions to the system (as the parameters vary over all real numbers)</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>matrix</title>
		<idx><h>matrix</h></idx>
		<p>a rectangular array of numbers</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>augmented matrix</title>
		<idx><h>augmented matrix</h></idx>
		<idx><h>matrix</h><h>augmented</h></idx>
		<p>a matrix of the coefficients and constants in a linear system</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>matrix entry</title>
		<idx><h>matrix</h><h>entry</h></idx>
		<p>one of the numbers in a matrix; sometimes also referred to as a <term>matrix coefficient</term></p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>row</title>
		<idx><h>matrix</h><h>row</h></idx>
		<idx><h>row</h><h>in a matrix</h></idx>
		<p>a horizontal line of entries in a matrix</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>column</title>
		<idx><h>matrix</h><h>column</h></idx>
		<idx><h>column</h><h>in a matrix</h></idx>
		<p>a vertical line of entries in a matrix</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>elementary row operations</title>
		<idx><h>row operations</h><h>elementary</h></idx>
		<idx><h>elementary</h><h>row operations</h></idx>
		<p>
			the three basic operations that can be applied to an augmented matrix without changing the set of solutions to the corresponding linear system:
			<ol marker="(i)">
				<li>swap the positions of two rows,</li>
				<li>multiply a row by a nonzero constant, and</li>
				<li>add a multiple of one row to another.</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
